{"title_page": "Victoria Pendergast", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name          = Victoria Pendergast\n| image         = PENDERGAST Victoria.2013 Processing.JPG| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Victoria Pendergast April 2013\n| fullname      =\n| nicknames     =\n| headercolor   = green\n| textcolor     = yellow\n| nationality   = {{AUS}}\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1991|01|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Gosford, New South Wales]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| residence     = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| country       = Australia\n| sport         = [[Para-alpine skiing]]\n| event         = [[Downhill (ski competition)|Downhill]]<br/>[[Super-G]]<br/>[[Giant Slalom]]<br/>[[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]\n| disability_class = [[LW12]]\n| worlds        = \n| regionals     = \n| nationals     = \n| paralympics   = \n| pb            = \n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n\n'''Victoria \"Tori\" Pendergast''' (born 25 January 1991) is an Australian [[Disability sport classification#Athletics|F58]] athletics [[shotput|shot put]] competitor and [[LW12]].1 classified [[para-alpine skiing|Para-alpine skier]]. When she competed at the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Sochi]], she became Australia's first female [[sit-ski|sit skier]] at the Winter Paralympics. She competed in two events, finishing seventh in women's [[Slalom skiing|slalom]] sit-ski and tenth in the women's [[giant slalom]] sit-ski. She also won a silver and a bronze medal in the slalom and [[super-G]] at the 2013 North America Cup, and a bronze medal in the giant slalom at the 2013 IPC World Cup in [[Thredbo]].\n\n==Personal==\nVictoria \"Tori\" Pendergast was born in [[Gosford]], [[New South Wales]] on 25 January 1991.<ref name=apcprofile/> She has [[sacral agenesis]], and was born missing the lower part of her spine.<ref name=apcprofile/> She attended [[Loreto Normanhurst]], and in 2013 she graduated with a degree in business and marketing from the [[University of Technology, Sydney]].<ref name=apcprofile/><ref name=utsstuff>{{cite web|url=http://www.utsunion.uts.edu.au/sports/victoriapendergast11.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321055231/http://www.utsunion.uts.edu.au/sports/victoriapendergast11.pdf|archivedate=21 March 2012|publisher=University of Technology, Sydney|accessdate=21 November 2012|location=Sydney, Australia|title=Victoria Pendergast|year=2011}}</ref> In early 2014, she was working as a telemarketer.<ref name=apcprofile>{{cite web|title=Victoria Pendergast|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/victoria-pendergast|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> She is an [[Disability sport classification#Athletics|F58 classified]] [[shot put]] competitor who finished 8th in the Girls Shot Put Disability Open at the 2004 Schools Athletics Championships.<ref name=f58class>{{cite news|title=Your Games: School and Weekend Club Results \u2013 Part Two of Four|newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 June 2004|author=MATP|page=38|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATLB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=105465A5F1EFE40E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref>\n\n==Skiing==\n[[File:Victoria Pendergast competing in the Super G during the second day of the 2012 IPC Nor Am Cup at Copper Mountain.jpg|thumb|right|Victoria Pendergast competing in the Super G during the second day of the 2012 IPC Nor Am Cup at [[Copper Mountain (Colorado)|Copper Mountain]]]]\nPendergast is an [[LW12]].1 classified skier,<ref name=classification>{{cite web|url=http://japanpara.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/SG_Female.pdf|publisher=Japan Paralympics|location=Japan|date=22 March 2012|title=2012 Japan Para Alpine Ski Championships|accessdate=21 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322055819/http://japanpara.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/SG_Female.pdf|archive-date=22 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> the classification for athletes \"with good sitting balance... and double above knee limb loss.\"<ref name=\"Sochi Media Guide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/sites/default/files/APC_Media%20Guide_Sochi%202014%20Winter%20Paralympic%20Games_WEB.pdf |accessdate=13 April 2014 |title=2014 Australian Paralympic Winter Team Media Guide |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She was spotted on the slopes by officials from Disabled Winter Sports Australia during a family ski holiday.<ref name=apcprofile/> This led to her participation in Athlete Development Programs run by Disabled Winter Sports Australia.<ref name=utsstuff/> Born missing the lower part of her spine, she is suited to [[monoski|sit-skiing]] and embraced hurtling down a mountain at {{convert|80|kph}} in a custom built sled.<ref name=couriermail/> She made her international debut at the New Zealand Winter Games in 2010.<ref name=apcprofile/>\n\nDuring the North American 2010/2011 skiing season, Pendergast was based in [[Avon, Colorado]], and competed in eight races, where she earned four bronze medals and a silver medal, and finished the season ranked 66th.<ref name=competed8races>{{cite web|url=http://skiracing.nastar.com/index.jsp?pagename=results&page=comp&compid=775291&year=2011 |title=The Next Generation of Ski & Snowboarding Racing! |publisher=Ski Racing : Nastar.com |date=15 September 2006 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> That season, she also participated in a 2-month long national development team training camp in Colorado.<ref name=utsstuff/> As a member of Australia's development team, she competed at a competition in December 2012 at [[Copper Mountain (Colorado)|Copper Mountain]],<ref name=competingcolor>{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/news/winning-start-winter-season |title=Winning start to winter season |location=New South Wales, Australia |publisher=APC Corporate |date=16 December 2011 |accessdate=21 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817235032/https://www.paralympic.org.au/news/winning-start-winter-season |archive-date=17 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and at the 2012 Japan Para Alpine Ski Championships in the women's sitting [[super-G]] event.<ref name=classification/><ref name=2012team>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/ipc-celebrates-women-alpine-skiing |title=IPC Celebrates Women in Alpine Skiing |publisher=International Paralympic Committee |date=13 August 2011 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nPendergast won a silver and bronze medal in the [[Slalom skiing|slalom]] and super G at the 2013 North America Cup, and a bronze medal in the [[giant slalom]] at the 2013 IPC World Cup in [[Thredbo]].<ref name=\"couriermail\">{{cite news|last=Lulham|first=Amanda|title=Paralympic ski newcomer Tori Pendergast setting her sights on winning a medal at Sochi|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/more-sports/paralympic-ski-newcomer-tori-pendergast-setting-her-sights-on-winning-a-medal-at-sochi/story-fnii0hmo-1226760313889|accessdate=11 February 2014|newspaper=Courier Mail|date=15 November 2013}}</ref> By February 2014, she was ranked 12th in the world in [[Downhill (ski competition)|downhill]] and giant slalom, and 13th in slalom and super-G.<ref name=\"Sochi Media Guide\"/>\n\nAt the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Sochi]], Pendergast became Australia's first ever female [[sit-ski|sit skier]] at the Winter Paralympics.<ref name=abc>{{cite web|title=Australia names Winter Paralympics team for Sochi including 14-year-old Para-snowboarder Ben Tudhope|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-02-04/australia-names-winter-paralympics-team-for-sochi/5236974|publisher=ABC News |date=5 February 2014|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> She competed in two events, finishing seventh in the women's slalom sit-ski and tenth in the women's giant slalom sit-ski.<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=Sochi 2014 Latest Results |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/sochi-2014/latest-results/latest-results |work=Australian Paralympic Committee |accessdate=17 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316222545/http://www.paralympic.org.au/sochi-2014/latest-results/latest-results |archivedate=16 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nPendergast competed in three Women's Sitting events at the 2015 [[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]] in [[Panorama Mountain Village|Panorama]], [[Canada]]. She finished sixth in the Slalom but did not finish the Super-G and Giant Slalom.<ref name=ipc>{{cite web|title=Victoria Pendergast|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Athletes/Biographies|website=International Parlympic Committee Athlete Profiles|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 Winter Paralympics]], her second Games, she finished fourth in the Women's Downhill Sitting and eighth in the Women's Giant Slalom.<ref>{{cite web |title=Victoria Pendergast |url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/redirect/ipc.asp?page=athletebio&personid=1103498&sportid=564 |website=International Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"announcement\">{{cite web|title=Australian Paralympic Winter Team for PyeongChang 2018 announced|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/australian-paralympic-winter-team-for-pyeongchang-2018-announced/|website=Australian Paralympic Committee website|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 World Para Alpine Skiing Championships]] in [[Kranjska Gora]], [[Slovenia]], she competed in two events but failed to finish.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tori Pendergast Results 2019 World Para Skiing World Championships |url=https://www.paralympic.org/sella-nevea-kranjska-gora-2019/schedule-results/info-live-results/asfa19/eng/zb/engzb_alpine-skiing-athlete-profile-n14426-pendergast-victoria.htm |website=International Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikinews|Wikinews interviews Australian sit skier Victoria Pendergast}}\n* [http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/victoria-pendergast Victoria Pendergast] at the [[Australian Paralympic Committee]]\n* {{IPC athlete|id=victoria-pendergast|old_id=1103498}}\n* {{YouTube|id=visrr1EI4dQ|title=Victoria Pendergast (2nd run) Women's slalom sitting at Sochi 2014 Paralympics}}\n* {{YouTube|id=si3gwYTPpSw|title=Victoria Pendergast (2nd run) Women's giant slalom sitting at Sochi 2014 Paralympics}}\n\n{{2014 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{2018 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pendergast, Victoria}}\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2014 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Amputee category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:People from Gosford]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:People with caudal regression syndrome]]\n[[Category:Australian female alpine skiers]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name          = Victoria Pendergast\n| image         = PENDERGAST Victoria.2013 Processing.JPG| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Victoria Pendergast April 2013\n| fullname      =\n| nicknames     =\n| headercolor   = green\n| textcolor     = yellow\n| nationality   = {{AUS}}\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1991|01|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Gosford, New South Wales]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| residence     = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| country       = Australia\n| sport         = [[Para-alpine skiing]]\n| event         = [[Downhill (ski competition)|Downhill]]<br/>[[Super-G]]<br/>[[Giant Slalom]]<br/>[[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]\n| disability_class = [[LW12]]\n| worlds        = \n| regionals     = \n| nationals     = \n| paralympics   = \n| pb            = \n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n\n'''Victoria \"Tori\" Pendergast''' (born 25 January 1991) is an Australian [[Disability sport classification#Athletics|F58]] athletics [[shotput|shot put]] competitor and [[LW12]].1 classified [[para-alpine skiing|Para-alpine skier]]. When she competed at the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Sochi]], she became Australia's first female [[sit-ski|sit skier]] at the Winter Paralympics. She competed in two events, finishing seventh in women's [[Slalom skiing|slalom]] sit-ski and tenth in the women's [[giant slalom]] sit-ski. She also won a silver and a bronze medal in the slalom and [[super-G]] at the 2013 North America Cup, and a bronze medal in the giant slalom at the 2013 IPC World Cup in [[Thredbo]].\n\n==Personal==\nVictoria \"Tori\" Pendergast was born in [[Gosford]], [[New South Wales]] on 25 January 1991.<ref name=apcprofile/> She has [[sacral agenesis]], and was born missing the lower part of her spine.<ref name=apcprofile/> She attended [[Loreto Normanhurst]], and in 2013 she graduated with a degree in business and marketing from the [[University of Technology, Sydney]].<ref name=apcprofile/><ref name=utsstuff>{{cite web|url=http://www.utsunion.uts.edu.au/sports/victoriapendergast11.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321055231/http://www.utsunion.uts.edu.au/sports/victoriapendergast11.pdf|archivedate=21 March 2012|publisher=University of Technology, Sydney|accessdate=21 November 2012|location=Sydney, Australia|title=Victoria Pendergast|year=2011}}</ref> In early 2014, she was working as a telemarketer.<ref name=apcprofile>{{cite web|title=Victoria Pendergast|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/victoria-pendergast|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> She is an [[Disability sport classification#Athletics|F58 classified]] [[shot put]] competitor who finished 8th in the Girls Shot Put Disability Open at the 2004 Schools Athletics Championships.<ref name=f58class>{{cite news|title=Your Games: School and Weekend Club Results \u2013 Part Two of Four|newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 June 2004|author=MATP|page=38|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATLB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=105465A5F1EFE40E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref>\n\n==Skiing==\n[[File:Victoria Pendergast competing in the Super G during the second day of the 2012 IPC Nor Am Cup at Copper Mountain.jpg|thumb|right|Victoria Pendergast competing in the Super G during the second day of the 2012 IPC Nor Am Cup at [[Copper Mountain (Colorado)|Copper Mountain]]]]\nPendergast is an [[LW12]].1 classified skier,<ref name=classification>{{cite web|url=http://japanpara.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/SG_Female.pdf|publisher=Japan Paralympics|location=Japan|date=22 March 2012|title=2012 Japan Para Alpine Ski Championships|accessdate=21 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322055819/http://japanpara.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/SG_Female.pdf|archive-date=22 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> the classification for athletes \"with good sitting balance... and double above knee limb loss.\"<ref name=\"Sochi Media Guide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/sites/default/files/APC_Media%20Guide_Sochi%202014%20Winter%20Paralympic%20Games_WEB.pdf |accessdate=13 April 2014 |title=2014 Australian Paralympic Winter Team Media Guide |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She was spotted on the slopes by officials from Disabled Winter Sports Australia during a family ski holiday.<ref name=apcprofile/> This led to her participation in Athlete Development Programs run by Disabled Winter Sports Australia.<ref name=utsstuff/> Born missing the lower part of her spine, she is suited to [[monoski|sit-skiing]] and embraced hurtling down a mountain at {{convert|80|kph}} in a custom built sled.<ref name=couriermail/> She made her international debut at the New Zealand Winter Games in 2010.<ref name=apcprofile/>\n\nDuring the North American 2010/2011 skiing season, Pendergast was based in [[Avon, Colorado]], and competed in eight races, where she earned four bronze medals and a silver medal, and finished the season ranked 66th.<ref name=competed8races>{{cite web|url=http://skiracing.nastar.com/index.jsp?pagename=results&page=comp&compid=775291&year=2011 |title=The Next Generation of Ski & Snowboarding Racing! |publisher=Ski Racing : Nastar.com |date=15 September 2006 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> That season, she also participated in a 2-month long national development team training camp in Colorado.<ref name=utsstuff/> As a member of Australia's development team, she competed at a competition in December 2012 at [[Copper Mountain (Colorado)|Copper Mountain]],<ref name=competingcolor>{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/news/winning-start-winter-season |title=Winning start to winter season |location=New South Wales, Australia |publisher=APC Corporate |date=16 December 2011 |accessdate=21 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817235032/https://www.paralympic.org.au/news/winning-start-winter-season |archive-date=17 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and at the 2012 Japan Para Alpine Ski Championships in the women's sitting [[super-G]] event.<ref name=classification/><ref name=2012team>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/ipc-celebrates-women-alpine-skiing |title=IPC Celebrates Women in Alpine Skiing |publisher=International Paralympic Committee |date=13 August 2011 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nPendergast won a silver and bronze medal in the [[Slalom skiing|slalom]] and super G at the 2013 North America Cup, and a bronze medal in the [[giant slalom]] at the 2013 IPC World Cup in [[Thredbo]].<ref name=\"couriermail\">{{cite news|last=Lulham|first=Amanda|title=Paralympic ski newcomer Tori Pendergast setting her sights on winning a medal at Sochi|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/more-sports/paralympic-ski-newcomer-tori-pendergast-setting-her-sights-on-winning-a-medal-at-sochi/story-fnii0hmo-1226760313889|accessdate=11 February 2014|newspaper=Courier Mail|date=15 November 2013}}</ref> By February 2014, she was ranked 12th in the world in [[Downhill (ski competition)|downhill]] and giant slalom, and 13th in slalom and super-G.<ref name=\"Sochi Media Guide\"/>\n\nAt the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Sochi]], Pendergast became Australia's first ever female [[sit-ski|sit skier]] at the Winter Paralympics.<ref name=abc>{{cite web|title=Australia names Winter Paralympics team for Sochi including 14-year-old Para-snowboarder Ben Tudhope|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-02-04/australia-names-winter-paralympics-team-for-sochi/5236974|publisher=ABC News |date=5 February 2014|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> She competed in two events, finishing seventh in the women's slalom sit-ski and tenth in the women's giant slalom sit-ski.<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=Sochi 2014 Latest Results |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/sochi-2014/latest-results/latest-results |work=Australian Paralympic Committee |accessdate=17 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316222545/http://www.paralympic.org.au/sochi-2014/latest-results/latest-results |archivedate=16 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nPendergast competed in three Women's Sitting events at the 2015 [[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]] in [[Panorama Mountain Village|Panorama]], [[Canada]]. She finished sixth in the Slalom but did not finish the Super-G and Giant Slalom.<ref name=ipc>{{cite web|title=Victoria Pendergast|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Athletes/Biographies|website=International Parlympic Committee Athlete Profiles|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 Winter Paralympics]], her second Games, she finished fourth in the Women's Downhill Sitting and eighth in the Women's Giant Slalom.<ref>{{cite web |title=Victoria Pendergast |url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/redirect/ipc.asp?page=athletebio&personid=1103498&sportid=564 |website=International Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"announcement\">{{cite web|title=Australian Paralympic Winter Team for PyeongChang 2018 announced|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/australian-paralympic-winter-team-for-pyeongchang-2018-announced/|website=Australian Paralympic Committee website|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 World Para Alpine Skiing Championships]] in [[Kranjska Gora]], [[Slovenia]], she competed in two events but failed to finish.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tori Pendergast Results 2019 World Para Skiing World Championships |url=https://www.paralympic.org/sella-nevea-kranjska-gora-2019/schedule-results/info-live-results/asfa19/eng/zb/engzb_alpine-skiing-athlete-profile-n14426-pendergast-victoria.htm |website=International Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikinews|Wikinews interviews Australian sit skier Victoria Pendergast}}\n* [http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/victoria-pendergast Victoria Pendergast] at the [[Australian Paralympic Committee]]\n* {{IPC athlete|1103498}}\n* {{YouTube|id=visrr1EI4dQ|title=Victoria Pendergast (2nd run) Women's slalom sitting at Sochi 2014 Paralympics}}\n* {{YouTube|id=si3gwYTPpSw|title=Victoria Pendergast (2nd run) Women's giant slalom sitting at Sochi 2014 Paralympics}}\n\n{{2014 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{2018 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pendergast, Victoria}}\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2014 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Amputee category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:People from Gosford]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:People with caudal regression syndrome]]\n[[Category:Australian female alpine skiers]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria_Pendergast"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad Shafiq", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Muhammad Shafiq {{flagicon|PAK}}\n| native_name = {{lang-ur|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0641\u06cc\u0642}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = 3rd [[Asian Handball Federation|Secretary General of Asian Handball Federation]]\n| term_start = 25 October 2013\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah]] {{flagicon|KUW}}\n| predecessor = Dr. Roshan Anand {{flagicon|IND}}\n| successor = \n| office1= [[Pakistan Olympic Association|Treasurer of Pakistan Olympic Association]]\n| term_start1= 4 February 2012\n| term_end1= \n| president1= [[Syed Arif Hasan]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Major]] Muhammad Afzal\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = 3rd [[Pakistan Handball Federation|President of Pakistan Handball Federation]]\n| term_start2 = December 2012\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = Syed Muhammad Abid Qadri\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = 1st & 3rd [[Pakistan Handball Federation|Secretary General of Pakistan Handball Federation]]\n| term_start3 = February 2007\n| term_end3 = December 2012\n| president3 = Syed Muhammad Abid Qadri\n| predecessor3 = Muhammad Faheem\n| successor3 = Khalid Rashid\n| term_start4 = April 1985\n| term_end4 = December 2004\n| president4 = Ahsan Alam\n| predecessor4 = ''Position created''\n| successor4 = Muhammad Faheem\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Faisalabad]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]] (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = [[Pakistan]]i\n| party = \n| otherparty = \n| height = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| education = [[M.S.|M. Sc.]] in Health and Physical Education, <br> M. Sc. in Rural Sociology, <br> Sports Specialisation Course (Athletics Coach)\n| alma_mater = [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad]] <br> [[University of Mainz]] <br> [[Gomal University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Sports administrator\n| known_for = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| awards = [[IHF Badge of Merit]] (Gold)\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| blank1 = Religion\n| data1 = [[Sunni Islam]]\n| footnotes = }}\n'''Muhammad Shafiq''' ({{lang-ur|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0641\u06cc\u0642}}; born 11 November 1953) is a [[Pakistan]]i sports administrator and former [[track and field]] athlete. He is [[Asian Handball Federation#AHF Secretary Generals|3rd]] and current Secretary General of [[Asian Handball Federation]] (AHF) since 25 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1051840/shafiq-elected-ahf-secretary-general |title=Shafiq elected AHF secretary-general |work=[[Dawn\u00a0(newspaper)|Dawn Newspaper]]'s Website |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> He is also holds the position of President in [[Pakistan Handball Federation]] since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/amp/172686-Shafiq-re-elected-Handball-Federation-president |title=Shafiq re-elected Handball Federation president |work=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMuhammad Shafiq was born on 11 November 1953 in [[Faisalabad]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]]. He competed in several editions of the [[National Games of Pakistan]], winning gold medal in 3000m steeplechase in 1976 edition held at [[Karachi]], gold medal in both 1500m and 3000m steeplechase in 1980 edition held at Karachi. He also participate in various international tournaments which includes [[1995 World Masters Athletics Championships|11th]], [[1999 World Masters Athletics Championships|13th]] and [[2001 World Masters Athletics Championships|14th]] edition of [[World Masters Athletics Championships]] where he stood 1st among the Asian athletes in his age category.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RNbpX4eT6ji4es2QnExTeNyhUeoZP4xh/view?usp=embed_facebook |title=Buffalo 1995.pdf |work=Google Docs |pages=23 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe completed his [[Master of Science]] degree in [[Rural Sociology]] from [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad]] in 1981 and then his Master of Science degree in Health and Physical Education from [[Gomal University]], [[Dera Ismail Khan]] in 1990. He had also done a Sports Specialization Course (Athletics trainer) from [[University of Mainz|Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], [[Germany]] in 1982.\n\nHe is fluent in [[English language|English]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and also speaks a little bit of [[German language|German]]. He is married and has one wife and four children, two daughters and two sons.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nHe started working as Assistant Director of Sports at University of Agriculture, Faisalabad in 1985. In 1990, he was promoted to Director of Sports and served in this position till his superannuation in 2013. During his tenure University of Agriculture, Faisalabad won All-Pakistan Inter-Universities Sports Championships All Round Trophy (Men) in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=UAF VC Prof. Dr. Iqrar Ahmad Khan addresses the participants of closing ceremony of handball training course at UAF |url=http://uaf.edu.pk/Events_2012/events/121103.html |publisher=www.uaf.edu.pk |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UAF Sports achievements 2008 to 2016 |url=http://uaf.edu.pk/directorates/sports/Files/Achivements-DS-2008-2016.pdf |publisher=www.uaf.edu.pk |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sports administration==\n===Asian Handball Federation===\nShafiq entered in [[Asian Handball Federation]] (AHF) in 1992, holding the position of member in [[AHF Council#AHF Promotion and Public Relations Commission|AHF Promotion and Public Relations Commission]] (1992 \u2013 1999) and [[AHF Council#AHF Playing Rules and Referees Commission|AHF Playing Rules and Referees Commission]] (1996 \u2013 2000) before being elected to [[AHF Council]] as Chairman of [[AHF Council#AHF Under Development Countries Commission|AHF Under Development Countries Commission]] (2004 \u2013 2009) and then as Chairman of [[AHF Council#AHF Commission of Youth and School Handball|AHF Commission of Youth and School Handball]] (2009 \u2013 2013). On 25 October 2013, he succeeded [[India]]n sports administrator Dr. Roshan Anand and was elected as AHF Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shafiq elected AHF secretary-general |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1051840/shafiq-elected-ahf-secretary-general |publisher=www.dawn.com |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan Handball Federation===\nShafiq is founder of [[handball]] in Pakistan. He is also the co-founder of [[Pakistan Handball Federation]] (PHF) in April 1985 and was elected as its Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Pakistan Handball |url=http://pakistanhandball.com/about-club |publisher=www.pakistanhandball.com |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He is the longest serving PHF Secretary General, holding the position for 24 years from 1985 \u2013 2004 and then from 2007 \u2013 2012. Currently, he is PHF President since December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Handball federation elects office-bearers |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1302924/handball-federation-elects-office-bearers |publisher=www.dawn.com |accessdate= December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Shafiq re-elected Handball Federation president |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/amp/172686-Shafiq-re-elected-Handball-Federation-president |publisher=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate= December 18, 2016}}</ref> Under his leadership, the performance of [[Pakistan national handball team]] and [[Pakistan national beach handball team]] are at their best as they won many medals which includes gold medal in 2nd edition of [[Asian Beach Handball Championship]] 2007 held at [[Bandar Abbas]], gold medal in [[Beach handball at the 2008 Asian Beach Games|1st Asian Beach Games 2008]] held at [[Bali]], and gold medals in 2010 and [[Handball at the 2019 South Asian Games \u2013 Men|2019]] editions of the [[Handball at the South Asian Games|South Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistanhandball.com/achievement/ |title=Achievement |work=www.pakistanhandball.com |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nShafiq also held various positions in other sports federations which includes Treasurer of [[Pakistan Olympic Association]] since February 2012 to till date.<ref>{{cite web |title=Syed Arif Hasan elected Pakistan Olympic Association President for record fourth term |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1033681/syed-arif-hasan-elected-pakistan-olympic-association-president-for-record-fourth-term |publisher=www.insidethegames.biz |accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Arif set to be elected unopposed POA president for another term |url=https://www.geo.tv/amp/258101-arif-set-to-be-elected-unopposed-poa-president-for-another-term |publisher=www.geo.tv |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref> He was elected as Vice-President (1991 \u2013 2000; 2009 \u2013 2013) and Secretary General (2000 \u2013 2009) of [[South Asian Handball Federation]]. He is a Member of Working Group of [[Commonwealth Handball Association]] and National Course Director of Pakistan NOC. He is also a member of [[International Track and Field Coaches Association]] since 1985.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shafiq, Muhammad}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Asian Handball Federation]]\n[[Category:Pakistani sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category:University of Agriculture, Faisalabad alumni]]\n[[Category:Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz alumni]]\n[[Category:Gomal University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Faisalabad]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Muhammad Shafiq {{flagicon|PAK}}\n| native_